Tom Lehrer's "Poisoning Pigeons in the Park," released in 1959, is a darkly humorous song that uses satire to address serious issues [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-0) [wildingthepyrenees](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-1) [luath](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-2). The song's meaning can be understood on several levels:

*   **Satire and Black Humor:** The song is a prime example of Lehrer's signature style of black humor, also known as dark comedy [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-0). It juxtaposes a cheerful, waltz-like melody with disturbing lyrics about poisoning pigeons, creating a jarring and unsettling effect [nyfos](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-3). This contrast is a key element of the song's comedic impact [nyfos](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-3).

*   **Social Commentary:** Lehrer's songs often parodied popular musical forms while addressing taboo subjects and political issues [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-0) [luath](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-2) [dramainthehood](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-4). "Poisoning Pigeons in the Park" is said to be inspired by the city of Boston's actual practice of controlling pigeon populations by using strychnine-laced corn in public parks [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-5) [wildingthepyrenees](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-1) [minnichmusic](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-6) [reddit](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-7). The song satirizes the nonchalant attitude towards such practices [wildingthepyrenees](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-1).

*   **The Absurdity of Violence:** The song presents a disturbing act in a lighthearted manner, prompting listeners to reflect on the absurdity and casualness with which violence can be normalized [minnichmusic](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-6) [nyfos](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-3).

*   **Musical Dissonance:** The song's humor comes from the ludicrous lyrical dissonance, which might be compared with the Frank Zappa track "Why Does It Hurt When I Pee?" [songfacts](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-8). "Poisoning Pigeons In The Park" is a jaunty love song of sorts with deliberately awkward lyrics performed by Lehrer accompanying himself at the piano [songfacts](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-8).

The song's impact is heightened by the contrast between the upbeat music and the morbid subject matter [nyfos](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-3). The pianist hired for an orchestral version of the song reportedly fell off his bench when he heard the title [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-5). Despite its dark themes, "Poisoning Pigeons in the Park" remains a popular example of Lehrer's satirical genius and his ability to find humor in the macabre [luath](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-2) [nyfos](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-3).

Strychnine-laced corn was used to control pigeon populations in Boston public areas during the 1950s [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-5).
